ategory:German atheist writers]]\n[[Category:Burials at Frankfurt Main Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Continental philosophers]]\n[[Category:Critical theorists]]\n[[Category:Critics of Christianity]]\n[[Category:Cultural critics]]\n[[Category:Epistemologists]]\n[[Category:Flautists]]\n[[Category:German atheists]]\n[[Category:German Buddhist scholars]]\n[[Category:German ethicists]]\n[[Category:German eugenicists]]\n[[Category:German flautists]]\n[[Category:German logicians]]\n[[Category:German monarchists]]\n[[Category:German people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:German philologists]]\n[[Category:Humboldt University of Berlin faculty]]\n[[Category:Idealists]]\n[[Category:Kantian philosophers]]\n[[Category:Logicians]]\n[[Category:Metaphysicians]]\n[[Category:Monism]]\n[[Category:Moral philosophers]]\n[[Category:Ontologists]]\n[[Category:People from Gda\u0144sk]]\n[[Category:Phenomenologists]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of art]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of culture]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of education]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of ethics and morality]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of history]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of language]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of literature]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of logic]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of love]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of mind]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of psychology]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of religion]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of science]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of social science]]\n[[Category:Political philosophers]]\n[[Category:Social commentators]]\n[[Category:Social critics]]\n[[Category:Social philosophers]]\n[[Category:Theorists on Western civilization]]\n[[Category:University of G\u00f6ttingen alumni]]\n", "name_user": "GenoV84", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSources:Fixed location to 1 reference.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arthur_Schopenhauer"}
{"title_page": "Fox\u2013Fordyce disease", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical condition (new) \n| name            = Fox\u2013Fordyce disease \n| image           =  \n| caption         =  \n| \n| pronounce       =  \n| field           =  \n| synonyms        =  Apocrine [[miliaria]]\n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Fox\u2013Fordyce disease''' is a [[Chronic (medicine)|chronic]] blockage of the [[sweat gland]] ducts with a secondary, non-[[bacteria]]l inflammatory response to the [[secretion]]s and [[cell (biology)|cell]]ular debris in the [[cyst]]s.<ref name=\"Fitz2\">Freedberg, et al. (2003). ''Fitzpatrick's Dermatology in General Medicine''. (6th ed.). McGraw-Hill. p. 709. {{ISBN|0-07-138076-0}}.</ref> The inflammation is often accompanied by intense itching. In general, the disease often causes skin to darken near the affected area and raised bumps or papules to appear. In addition, hair follicles can become damaged which cause hair loss.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|url=https://escholarship.org/uc/item/6km4c88v|title=Fox-Fordyce disease|journal=Dermatology Online Journal|volume=18|issue=12|date=December 2012|last1=Meehan|first1=Shane A.|last2=Robinson|first2=Maria|last3=Yost|first3=John}}</ref>[[Hidradenitis]] is very similar, but tends to have a secondary bacterial infection so that pus-draining sinuses are formed. It is a very devastating [[skin]] disease that does not have universally curative treatments.\n\n==Signs & Symptoms==\nSymptoms may appear suddenly following any condition of heat, humidity, or friction. The apocrine glands (sweat glands) are the site of the Fox\u2013Fordyce disease. Sudden appearance of raised bumps (papules) near the apocrine glands is characteristic of the disease. Papules are mostly skin colored, dome shaped, and itchy. Papules can be found at the sweat glands in addition to periareolar, inframammary and pubic areas. Hair follicles can become damaged as well and can result in hair loss in the affected area.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://rarediseases.org/rare-diseases/fox-fordyce-disease/|title=Fox Fordyce Disease|website=NORD (National Organization for Rare Disorders)}}</ref>\n\n== Causes ==\nExact cause of Fox-Fordyce is currently unknown. Studies have not been able to confirm if apocrine gland duct obstruction is required for development. It is speculated that gland duct rupture causes inflammation. Inflammatory response includes white blood cells.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Diagnosis ==\nClinical evaluation along with identification of typical symptoms such as the eruption of papules on the apocrine glands along with a patient history report is used to diagnose the disease. Surgical removal along with a microscopic evaluation by a dermatopathologist is the most reliable form of diagnosis.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Treatment==\nWith only a small number of case reports, treatment can be difficult and focuses primarily on axillary disease and specific symptoms. First line treatment includes topical and intralesional glucocorticoids. Specific therapies include estrogen hormones and steroid creams. Use of tretinoin reduced pruritic and axillary papules in one study. However, irritation limited drug use to short term only. Clindamycin mixed with pimecrolimus cream and benzoyl peroxide was also effective. Clindamycin is used to inhibit bacterial growth and is used when treating staphylococcal and streptococcal infections.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Epidemiology==\nMost commonly affects women aged 13\u201335 years, approximately puberty through their prime. Some reports show affected women to men at 9:1. Rare cases have been shown to affect post-menopausal women, children, and men. Incident report is currently unknown. Although rare, men and children have been shown to be affected. Heat, humidity, stress, and exercise have been shown to worsen symptoms.  Rate of incidence is currently unknown. Fox-Fordyce has also been shown to be severe during menstruation and spontaneously disappear during pregnancy<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Eponym==\nIt is named for [[George Henry Fox]] and [[John Addison Fordyce]].<ref>{{WhoNamedIt|synd|1512}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1001/archderm.138.1.16 |title=Two Cases of a Rare Papular Disease Affecting the Axillary Region |journal=Archives of Dermatology |volume=138 |issue=1 |pages=16 |year=2002 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of cutaneous conditions]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{EMedicine|article|1070560|Fox-Fordyce Disease}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n| DiseasesDB      = 30029\n| ICD10           = {{ICD10|L|75|2|l|60}}\n| ICD9            = {{ICD9|705.82}}\n| ICDO            = \n| OMIM            = \n| MedlinePlus     = \n| eMedicineSubj   = derm\n| eMedicineTopic  = 160\n| MeshID          = D005588\n| SNOMED CT       = 65038009\n}}\n{{Disorders of skin appendages}}\n{{Medicine}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fox-Fordyce disease}}\n[[Category:Conditions of the skin appendages]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical condition (new) \n| name            = Fox\u2013Fordyce disease \n| image           =  \n| caption         =  \n| \n| pronounce       =  \n| field           =  \n| synonyms        =  Apocrine [[miliaria]]\n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Fox\u2013Fordyce disease''' is a [[Chronic (medicine)|chronic]] blockage of the [[sweat gland]] ducts with a secondary, non-[[bacteria]]l inflammatory response to the [[secretion]]s and [[cell (biology)|cell]]ular debris in the [[cyst]]s.<ref name=\"Fitz2\">Freedberg, et al. (2003). ''Fitzpatrick's Dermatology in General Medicine''. (6th ed.). McGraw-Hill. p. 709. {{ISBN|0-07-138076-0}}.</ref> The inflammation is often accompanied by intense itching. In general, the disease often causes skin to darken near the affected area and raised bumps or papules to appear. In addition, hair follicles can become damaged which cause hair loss.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|url=https://escholarship.org/uc/item/6km4c88v|title=Fox-Fordyce disease|journal=Dermatology Online Journal|volume=18|issue=12|date=December 2012|last1=Meehan|first1=Shane A.|last2=Robinson|first2=Maria|last3=Yost|first3=John}}</ref>[[Hidradenitis]] is very similar, but tends to have a secondary bacterial infection so that pus-draining sinuses are formed. It is a very devastating [[skin]] disease that does not have universally curative treatments.\n\n==Signs & Symptoms==\nSymptoms may appear suddenly following any condition of heat, humidity, or friction. The apocrine glands (sweat glands) are the site of the Fox\u2013Fordyce disease. Sudden appearance of raised bumps (papules) near the apocrine glands is characteristic of the disease. Papules are mostly skin colored, dome shaped, and itchy. Papules can be found at the sweat glands in addition to periareolar, inframammary and pubic areas. Hair follicles can become damaged as well and can result in hair loss in the affected area.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://rarediseases.org/rare-diseases/fox-fordyce-disease/|title=Fox Fordyce Disease|website=NORD (National Organization for Rare Disorders)}}</ref>\n\n== Causes ==\nExact cause of Fox-Fordyce is currently unknown. Studies have not been able to confirm if apocrine gland duct obstruction is required for development. It is speculated that gland duct rupture causes inflammation. Inflammatory response includes white blood cells.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Diagnosis ==\nClinical evaluation along with identification of typical symptoms such as the eruption of papules on the apocrine glands along with a patient history report is used to diagnose the disease. Surgical removal along with a microscopic evaluation by a dermatopathologist is the most reliable form of diagnosis.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Treatment==\nWith only a small number of case reports, treatment can be difficult and focuses primarily on axillary disease and specific symptoms. First line treatment includes topical and intralesional glucocorticoids. Specific therapies include estrogen hormones and steroid creams. Use of tretinoin reduced pruritic and axillary papules in one study. However, irritation limited drug use to short term only. Clindamycin mixed with pimecrolimus cream and benzoyl peroxide was also effective. Clindamycin is used to inhibit bacterial growth and is used when treating staphylococcal and streptococcal infections.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Epidemiology==\nMost commonly affects women aged 13\u201335 years, approximately puberty through their prime. Some reports show affected women to men at 9:1. Rare cases have been shown to affect post-menopausal women, children, and men. Incident report is currently unknown. Although rare, men and children have been shown to be affected. Heat, humidity, stress, and exercise have been shown to worsen symptoms.  Rate of incidence is currently unknown. Fox-Fordyce has also been shown to be severe during menstruation and spontaneously disappear during pregnancy<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Eponym==\nIt is named for [[George Henry Fox]] and [[John Addison Fordyce]].<ref>{{WhoNamedIt|synd|1512}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1001/archderm.138.1.16 |title=Two Cases of a Rare Papular Disease Affecting the Axillary Region |journal=Archives of Dermatology |volume=138 |issue=1 |pages=16 |year=2002 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of cutaneous conditions]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{EMedicine|article|1070560|Fox-Fordyce Disease}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|   DiseasesDB     = 30029 \n|   ICD10          = {{ICD10|L|75|2|l|60}} \n|   ICD9           = {{ICD9|705.82}} \n|   ICDO           = \n|   OMIM           = \n|   MedlinePlus    = \n|   eMedicineSubj  = derm \n|   eMedicineTopic = 160 \n|   MeshID         = D005588 \n}}\n{{Disorders of skin appendages}}\n{{Medicine}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fox-Fordyce disease}}\n[[Category:Conditions of the skin appendages]]\n", "name_user": "Dismanet", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding new medical resources.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fox%E2%80%93Fordyce_disease"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Metro Manila", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Metro Manila}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Philippine English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Metro Manila\n| map1            = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Metro Manila.svg\n| legend1         = {{center|Map of cities with confirmed coronavirus cases by hospital of admission (as of March 12)}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Metro Manila]]\n| first_case      = [[Manila]]\n| arrival_date    = January 30, 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=30|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| recovery_cases  = 45\n| deaths          = 101\n| confirmed_cases = 728\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = https://www.doh.gov.ph/2019-nCoV\n}}\n\nThe first confirmed case of the [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in the [[Philippines]] was recorded in [[Metro Manila]] on January 30, 2020. It involved a 38-year-old Chinese woman from [[Wuhan]], the origin of the disease, who arrived in [[Manila]] after travelling to [[Cebu City]] and [[Dumaguete]] in central Philippines from [[Hong Kong]].<ref name=\"abs1\">{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/01/30/20/philippines-confirms-first-case-of-new-coronavirus |title=Philippines confirms first case of new coronavirus |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |author=Sabillo, K. |date=30 January 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref> Three days later, the [[Department of Health (Philippines)|Philippine Department of Health]] (DOH) confirmed that a second Chinese national tested positive for COVID-19, identified as the 44-year-old male companion of the first confirmed patient.<ref name=\"gma1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/724482/philippines-confirms-2nd-novel-coronavirus-case-patient-dies/story/ |title=Philippines confirms 2nd novel coronavirus case, 1st death outside China |publisher=[[GMA News]] |author=Colcol, E. |date=2 February 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\nBoth patients received treatment at Manila's [[San Lazaro Hospital, Manila|San Lazaro Hospital]] with the latter being reported to have died from the disease on February 2, becoming the first known fatality outside [[China]].<ref name=\"gma1\"/> On March 6, the DOH reported the first case of local community transmission of the deadly virus, a 62-year-old Filipino man from suburban [[Cainta]], [[Rizal]], just east of Metro Manila, with no prior travel history to affected countries.<ref name=\"cnn1\">{{cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/6/Philippines-coronavirus-local-case.html |title=Philippines records its first local case of coronavirus |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |author=Tan, L. |date=6 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref> He and his 59-year-old Filipino wife were initially admitted to the Cardinal Santos Medical Center in [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan]] where they were diagnosed with the virus before being transferred to the [[Research Institute for Tropical Medicine]] in [[Muntinlupa]] where they both died on March 11.<ref name=\"philstar2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/12/2000450/doh-first-local-transmission-wife-among-three-new-covid-19-deaths |title=First local COVID-19 transmission case, wife among 3 new deaths in Philippines |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=San Juan, R. |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, 2020, following the declaration of a public health emergency, Philippine President [[Rodrigo Duterte]] placed the entire capital region under community [[quarantine]] for 30 days starting March 15, 2020.<ref name=\"philstar1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/12/2000209/travel-and-manila-suspended-march-15-code-red-sublevel-2-raised-over-covid-19 |title=Travel to and from Manila suspended from March 15 as Code Red Sublevel 2 raised over COVID-19 |last=Luna |first=Franco |website=philstar.com |access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Most areas in Metro Manila have also issued curfews to help limit the spread of the virus.<ref name=\"gma2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/729731/manila-to-have-curfew-from-8-p-m-5-a-m-amid-covid-19-threat-says-mayor-isko/story/ |title=Several Metro Manila LGUs impose 8 p.m.-5 a.m. COVID-19 curfew |publisher=[[GMA News]] |author=Rita, J. |date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 29, 2020, there have been 1,546 confirmed cases of COVID-19 in the Philippines, 728 of which are residents of Metro Manila. There have been 101 reported deaths, with [[Quezon City]] and San Juan reporting the most fatalities. 45 people have recovered.<ref name=\"COVID-19 tracker\">{{cite web |title=COVID-19 Case Tracker |url=https://ncovtracker.doh.gov.ph/ |website=doh.gov.ph |publisher=[[Department of Health (Philippines)]] |accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Timeline ==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable floatright <!---mw-collapsible--->\" style=\"text-align:left; font-size:90%; width:auto; clear:right; margin:0 0 0.5em 1em;\"\n|+COVID-19 cases in NCR, Philippines<ref name=\"COVID-19 tracker\"/><br/><small>by city/municipality of residence<br/>Updated March 31, 2020 11:00 pm UTC+8</small>\n! {{abbr|LGU|Local government unit}}\n! {{Hover title|Confirmed cases|Cases}}\n! Deaths\n! {{abbr|Recov.|Recoveries}}\n|-\n| [[Caloocan]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 28\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 8\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 4\n|-\n| [[Las Pi\u00f1as]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 27\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 2\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 3\n|-\n| [[Makati]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 47\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 2\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 3\n|-\n| [[Malabon]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 8\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 2\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 1\n|-\n| [[Mandaluyong]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 60\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 6\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 2\n|-\n| [[Manila]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 75\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 10\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 4\n|-\n| [[Marikina]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 21\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 4\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 4\n|-\n| [[Muntinlupa]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 34\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 4\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | {{color|darkgray|0}}\n|-\n| [[Navotas]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 3\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 1\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | {{color|darkgray|0}}\n|-\n| [[Para\u00f1aque]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 39\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 9\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | {{color|darkgray|0}}\n|-\n| [[Pasay]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 22\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 1\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 1\n|-\n| [[Pasig]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 41\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 7\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 8\n|-\n| [[Pateros, Metro Manila|Pateros]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 1\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | {{color|darkgray|0}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | {{color|darkgray|0}}\n|-\n| [[Quezon City]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 151\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 27\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 11\n|-\n| [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 99\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 14\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 2\n|-\n| [[Taguig]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 62\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 3\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 2\n|-\n| [[Valenzuela, Metro Manila|Valenzuela]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 10\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 1\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | {{color|darkgray|0}}\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"text-align:left;\" | Total\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" | 728\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" | 101\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" | 45\n|-\n|}\n* '''January 30''' \u2013 The Philippines confirmed its first case of coronavirus in Metro Manila and the entire country after a 38-year-old woman from [[Wuhan]] tested positive for COVID-19. She was hospitalized at [[San Lazaro Hospital, Manila|San Lazaro Hospital]].<ref name=\"abs1\"/>\n* '''February 2''' \u2013 The first coronavirus-related death outside China was recorded in Manila. A 44-year-old Chinese man died while being treated at the San Lazaro Hospital.<ref name=\"gma1\"/>\n* '''March 6''' \u2013 The first case of community transmission was reported by the DOH, a 62-year-old Filipino man from nearby [[Cainta]] with no known history of travel abroad and who regularly visited a Muslim prayer hall in [[Greenhills (mixed-use development)|Greenhills]], San Juan.\n* '''March 9''' \u2013 The local governments of San Juan, [[Marikina]], and [[Pasay]] ordered the suspension of classes for all levels amid the announcement of the first case of community transmission in the metropolis.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/nation/2020/03/09/1999216/san-juan-marikina-pasay-suspend-classes-over-covid-19 |title=San Juan, Marikina, Pasay suspend classes over COVID-19 |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=Servallos, N.J. |date=9 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n* '''March 10'''\n** President [[Rodrigo Duterte]] ordered the closure of all schools, colleges, and universities in Metro Manila from March 10 to March 14.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/253912-walang-pasok-duterte-declares-class-suspensions-metro-manila-coronavirus-threat-march-10-14-2020 |title=Duterte suspends classes in Metro Manila March 10\u201314 over coronavirus threat |publisher=[[Rappler]] |author=Tomacruz, S. |date=9 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n** Marikina Mayor [[Marcelino Teodoro]] announced the cancellation of the [[2020 Palarong Pambansa]] as host city of the games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://businessmirror.com.ph/2020/03/10/marikina-calls-off-palaro/ |title=Marikina calls off Palaro |publisher=[[BusinessMirror]] |author=Bonilla, R.R.C. |date=10 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n* '''March 11''' \u2013 Manila Mayor [[Isko Moreno]] went into self-quarantine and isolated himself in the [[Manila City Hall]] after arriving from an official trip to [[London]], U.K.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/254164-isko-moreno-self-quarantines-manila-city-hall |title=Isko Moreno self-quarantines at Manila city hall |publisher=[[Rappler]] |author=Talabong, R. |date=11 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n* '''March 12'''\n** President Duterte announced a partial lockdown on Metro Manila, placing the entire Metro Manila under community quarantine for thirty days beginning on March 15. The suspension of classes in all levels in Metro Manila was extended to April 12.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/12/2000353/walang-pasok-duterte-suspends-metro-manila-classes-until-april-12 |title=Walang Pasok: Duterte suspends Metro Manila classes until April 12 |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=Patag, K.J. |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n** Incidents of [[panic buying]] have been reported across the region triggered by the president's partial lockdown order.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1240902/look-panic-buying-amid-lockdown-fears-in-metro |title=LOOK: Panic-buying amid lockdown fears in Metro Manila |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Marquez, C. |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n* '''March 13'''\n** The local chief executives of [[Caloocan]], [[Malabon]], [[Navotas]], and [[Valenzuela, Metro Manila|Valenzuela]]: [[Oscar Malapitan]], [[Antolin Oreta]], [[Toby Tiangco]], and [[Rex Gatchalian]], respectively, went into self-quarantine after learning they had come into contact with a confirmed coronavirus patient at a March 5 event in Caloocan's [[North Luzon Expressway]]\u2013Harbor Link.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1240982/camanava-mayors-under-quarantine |title=Camanava mayors under quarantine |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Adonis, M. |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Manila]] suspended all worship services and activities in their parishes across Metro Manila for seven days beginning March 14. The [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Cubao|Diocese of Cubao]], [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Novaliches|Diocese of Novaliches]], and [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Para\u00f1aque|Diocese of Para\u00f1aque]] have also issued a similar directive for their parishioners.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/254346-manila-churches-suspend-masses-coronavirus-lockdown |title=Manila churches suspend Masses amid coronavirus lockdown |publisher=[[Rappler]] |author=Esmaquel, P. |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n** The DOH reported that four COVID-19 patients in the region had died.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/13/qc-state-of-calamity.html |title=Quezon City declares state of calamity amid COVID-19 threat |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |author=CNN PH staff |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n* '''March 14'''\n** The [[University Athletic Association of the Philippines]] cancelled [[UAAP Season 82]] games and all other collegiate and high school tournaments in Metro Manila from March 15 to April 14.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/sports/content/729693/uaap-cancels-season-82-hs-tourneys-current-format-collegiate-matches-amid-covid-19-scare/story/ |title=UAAP cancels Season 82 HS tourneys, current format collegiate matches amid COVID-19 scare |publisher=[[GMA News]] |author=Santos, J. |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n** A mass exodus to the provinces was observed in the hours leading to the Metro Manila lockdown. Thousands were seen flocking to the provincial bus terminals such as the [[Araneta City Bus Port]] in Quezon City as well as the [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/254503-photos-mass-exodus-metro-manila-lockdown-coronavirus |title=IN PHOTOS: Mass exodus before Metro Manila 'lockdown' |publisher=[[Rappler]] |author=Rey, A. |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n* '''March 15'''\n** A total of 56 checkpoints were set up in numerous points of entry to Metro Manila on the first day of the partial lockdown.<ref name=\"partial lockdown\">{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1242619/police-seal-metro-manila-to-fight-virus |title=Police seal Metro Manila to fight virus |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Yamsuan, C.C., Agoncillo, J.A. |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n**Following a directive from the Metro Manila Council and the confirmation of COVID-19 cases, the city mayors of Makati, Manila, Pasig, and San Juan declare a [[State of emergency|state of calamity]].<ref name=\"state of calamity\"/>\n** Shopping mall chains [[Ayala Malls]] and [[SM Supermalls]] announced the temporary closure of all their establishments across Metro Manila. [[Robinsons Metro East]], [[Power Plant Mall]], and Greenhills have also closed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/lifestyle/shoppingandfashion/729778/metro-manila-malls-to-temporarily-close-amid-covid-19-threat/story/ |title=Metro Manila malls to temporarily close amid COVID-19 threat |publisher=[[GMA News]] |author=Cabuenas, J.V.D. |date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n** The [[Philippine Amusement and Gaming Corporation]] ordered the suspension of all gaming operations in Metro Manila, including the land-based casinos in [[Entertainment City]] and [[Newport City, Metro Manila|Newport City]]. The gaming regulator also announced that they were limiting the operations of [[Philippine offshore gaming operation]]s in the region.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/03/15/20/pagcor-suspends-casino-gaming-operations-during-metro-manila-quarantine |title=PAGCOR suspends casino, gaming operations during Metro Manila quarantine |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n* '''March 16'''\n** President Duterte [[2020 Luzon enhanced community quarantine|imposed an \"enhanced\" community quarantine]] covering the entire [[Luzon]], including Metro Manila, suspending [[Transportation in the Philippines|mass public transportation]]; restricting land, air, and sea travel; imposing strict home quarantine; and closing most private establishments until April 13.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/2020/03/16/memorandum-from-the-executive-secretary-on-community-quarantine-over-the-entire-luzon-and-further-guidelines-for-the-management-of-the-coronavirus-disease-2019-covid-19-situation/|title=Memorandum from the Executive Secretary On Community Quarantine Over the Entire Luzon and Further Guidelines for the Management of the Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) Situation|date=16 March 2020|work=Official Gazette GOV.PH|access-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n<center>\n{{Graph:Chart\n|width=700\n|colors=#FF6347\n|showValues=offset:2\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|type=rect\n|x=Jan 30, Mar 16, Mar 17, Mar 19, Mar 24, Mar 25, Mar 26, Mar 27, Mar 28, Mar 29, Mar 30, Mar 31\n|yAxisTitle=No. of cases\n|legend=Legend\n|y1=1, 93, 108, 143, 249, 328, 363, 412, 460, 539, 584, 728\n|y1Title=Total number of cases\n|yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n</center>\n\n== Response ==\n=== National government ===\n[[File:PNP PRO 3 Checkpoints COVID 19 2.jpg|thumb|Police checkpoint near the border of Metro Manila with [[Meycauayan]], [[Bulacan]] in [[Valenzuela, Metro Manila|Valenzuela]], March 19, 2020]]\nBefore the partial lockdown on Metro Manila declared on March 12, President [[Rodrigo Duterte]] had initially suspended classes across all levels in Metro Manila from March 10 to 14 upon reaching a consensus with the [[Metro Manila Council]] (the mayors of Metro Manila) due to the rapidly increasing number of cases especially in the area.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lopez |first1=Virgil |title=Duterte suspends classes in Metro Manila from March 10 to 14, 2020 |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/serbisyopubliko/walangpasok/728993/duterte-suspends-classes-in-metro-manila-from-march-10-to-14-2020/story/?just_in |accessdate=March 9, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, President Duterte announced a partial lockdown covering Metro Manila, that begun on March 15 and will last until April 14. Under the partial lockdown:<ref>{{cite news |last1=Santos |first1=Ana |title=Ghost town: Manila under coronavirus lockdown |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/manila-turns-ghost-town-coronavirus-lockdown-200315121507679.html |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Al Jazeera |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n* The region is closed to land, air, and sea travel. However, mass transportation within Metro Manila such as the [[Manila Light Rail Transit System|Manila LRT]] and [[Manila Metro Rail Transit System|MRT]] continues to operate under proper [[social distancing]] guidelines.\n* Suspension of classes at all levels in Metro Manila is extended until April 14.\n* Spontaneous and planned mass gatherings are banned.\n* Work in the Executive department is suspended under the lockdown period.\n* The [[Department of Labor and Employment (Philippines)|Department of Labor and Employment]] encourages employers in the private sector to arrange \"flexible work arrangements\".\n\nFollowing the declaration of the partial lockdown, the [[Metropolitan Manila Development Authority]] (MMDA) suspended the enforcement of the [[Unified Vehicular Volume Reduction Program]], more commonly known as the number coding scheme.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Santos |first1=Jel |title=Number coding suspended indefinitely due to 'community quarantine' \u2014 MMDA |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/13/number-coding-suspended-indefinitely-due-to-community-quarantine-mmda/ |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> On the eve of the Metro Manila lockdown, the MMDA announced the imposition of an area-wide [[curfew]] from 8{{nbsp}}p.m. to 5{{nbsp}}a.m. the following day to be observed during the lockdown, during which only \"essential movements\" for the purchase of essential needs or in cases of emergency are permitted during those hours.<ref>{{cite news |title=Curfew from 8 p.m. to 5 a.m. to take effect in Metro Manila under COVID-19 quarantine |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/14/20/metro-manila-quarantine-curfew |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> The Metro Manila Council unanimously approved the imposition of the curfew in a joint resolution. All local governments, except for [[Marikina]] and [[Pateros, Metro Manila|Pateros]], had adopted ordinances imposing the curfew in their respective cities, effective by March 20.<ref>{{cite news |title=LIST: Metro Manila cities with COVID-19 curfew |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/16/Metro-Manila-COVID-19-curfew-list.html |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> In that joint resolution, the council also ordered the closure of shopping malls and other establishments during the lockdown.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cordero |first1=Ted |title=Metro Manila Council wants malls temporarily closed amid COVID-19 threat |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/729652/metro-manila-council-wants-malls-temporarily-closed-amid-covid-19-threat/story/?just_in |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA total of 56 checkpoints were set up to man the borders of Metro Manila on the first day of the partial lockdown.<ref name=\"partial lockdown\"/> At 12 midnight, a total of 26,000 police and military personnel were deployed to contain the pandemic of COVID-19 in the region. Motorists were stopped randomly and asked for their identification along the borders in North Luzon Expressway, [[MacArthur Highway]], and the National Road ([[Maharlika Highway]]). Some checkpoints lacked thermal scanners.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/254565-metro-manila-lockdown-implementation-checkpoints-march-15-2020 |title=Day 1 of Metro Manila lockdown: Different checkpoints, different rules |publisher=[[Rappler]] |author=Cupin, B., Rivas, R. & Tomacruz, S. |date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nDespite the moratorium on mass public transportation during the \"enhanced\" community quarantine, Vice President [[Leni Robredo]] launched free shuttle bus services for those individuals exempted from the quarantine, specifically health professionals, front line government officials, and essential service providers. Robredo's shuttle services travel five routes around Metro Manila, connecting the major hospitals.<ref>{{cite news |title=Robredo donates gear to health workers, pledges free shuttle rides |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/17/robredo-donation-health-workers.html |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> Some city governments also deployed such transportation services.\n\nTo address concerns regarding the hoarding and [[panic buying]] of essential goods, some city governments issued ordinances to limit the amount of such goods an individual or establishment could purchase.<ref name=\"Muntinlupa anti-hoarding\">{{cite news |last1=Hicap |first1=Jonathan |title=Muntinlupa declares state of calamity due to COVID-19 |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/17/muntinlupa-declares-state-of-calamity-due-to-covid-19/ |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Pasig anti-hoarding\">{{cite news |last1=Ramos |first1=Christia Marie |title=Pasig City OKs anti-hoarding, panic buying ordinance |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1243408/pasig-city-anti-panic-buying-ordinance-story |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Valenzuela anti-hoarding\">{{cite news |last1=David |first1=Jun |title=Valenzuela passes anti-hoarding, anti-panic buying measure |url=https://manilastandard.net/index.php/lgu/ncr/319768/valenzuela-passes-anti-hoarding-anti-panic-buying-measure.html |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=Manila Standard |date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health]] has on March 20, 2020 has announced that it has designated three health facilities as COVID-19 referral hospitals namely the [[Philippine General Hospital|UP-Philippine General Hospital]] (UP-PGH) in Manila, the Dr. Jose M. Rodriguez Memorial Hospital and Sanitarium in Caloocan and the [[Lung Center of the Philippines]] in Quezon City. The UP-PGH has stopped admitting non-emergency cases and the Lung Center has dedicated one of its wings of 40 beds for COVID-19 patients. The Philippine Blood Center likewise will not admit any suspected COVID-19 cases with the health department encouraging the public to continue donate blood for COVID-19 patients with critical and severe conditions.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Galvez |first1=Daphne |title=PGH, 2 other institutions chosen as COVID-19 referral hospitals |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1245731/covid-19-referral-hospitals |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nVice President Robredo converted a [[dormitory]] in [[Quezon City#Cubao|Cubao, Quezon City]], to provide free accommodations for front line health professionals during the \"enhanced\" community quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Esguerra |first1=Darryl John |title=Robredo launches free dormitory in QC for COVID-19 frontliners |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1248747/robredo-launches-free-dormitory-in-qc-for-covid-19-frontliners |accessdate=March 28, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Local governments ===\n==== Caloocan ====\nOn March 10, [[Caloocan]] Mayor [[Oscar Malapitan]] announced that the city government had postponed several scheduled events, namely the Miss Caloocan Pageant, Mega Job Fairs, City Development Council General Assembly, Outstanding Citizens Awards Night, and Family Day activities, to prevent the spread of the virus amongst large crowds.<ref name=\"Caloocan, Valenzuela\">{{cite news |last1=Caybyab |first1=Marc Jayson |title=Caloocan, Valenzuela cancel events over COVID-19 |url=https://www.philstar.com/nation/2020/03/10/1999490/caloocan-valenzuela-cancel-events-over-covid-19 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, the Caloocan city council passed an ordinance imposing the 8{{nbsp}}p.m. to 5{{nbsp}}a.m. curfew agreed upon by the Metro Manila Council.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pedrajas |first1=Joseph Almer |title=Caloocan to strictly implement 8 pm-to-5 am curfew |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/16/caloocan-to-strictly-implement-8-pm-to-5-am-curfew/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, Mayor Malapitan announced that the Caloocan government would impose window hours on residents for the purchase of essential goods. Residents could only access the city's [[Palengke|public markets]] between 6{{nbsp}}a.m. to 9{{nbsp}}a.m. and 4{{nbsp}}p.m. to 7{{nbsp}}p.m., while supermarkets, banks, and pharmacies can only be accessed between 6{{nbsp}}a.m. to 7{{nbsp}}p.m. The city would also issue quarantine passes, permitting only one resident per household between the ages of 18 to 60 years old to leave their house solely for purchasing such goods.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marquez |first1=Consuelo |title=Caloocan gov\u2019t imposes window hours for buying basic goods |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1247566/caloocan-govt-imposes-window-hours-for-buying-basic-goods |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Las Pi\u00f1as ====\nOn March 14, [[Las Pi\u00f1as]] Mayor Imelda Aguilar declared a state of calamity in the city after a resident was confirmed to have tested positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |title=Las Pi\u00f1as declares state of calamity amid coronavirus alarm |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/14/20/las-pias-declares-state-of-calamity-amid-coronavirus-alarm |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, the Las Pi\u00f1as government began implementing a 24-hour curfew on its residents.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fernando |first1=Jean |title=Las Pi\u00f1as City imposes 24-hour curfew |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/21/las-pinas-city-imposes-24-hour-curfew/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Makati ====\n\nOn March 15, [[Makati]] Mayor [[Abigail Binay]] placed the city under a state of calamity after it was confirmed that three residents of [[Rockwell Center]] had contracted the flu virus.<ref name=\"state of calamity\"/>\n\nOn March 17, the Makati government launched free shuttle bus services for doctors, nurses, and other employees of the Ospital ng Makati, which runs between the hospital and certain points in the city.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gonzales |first1=Cathrine |title=Makati gov't deploys buses for OsMak, city hall employees |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1243764/makati-govt-deploys-buses-for-osmak-city-hall-employees |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> In addition, Mayor Binay announced that tricycle drivers affected by the moratorium would receive an initial {{Philippine peso|2,000|link=yes}} (US$39.23) financial assistance to cover the first two weeks of the quarantine. Binay added that a similar financial compensation would be given to jeepney drivers of the city.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gonzales |first1=Cathrine |title=Makati to give P2,000-financial aid to city's tricycle drivers |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1244295/makati-to-give-p2000-to-citys-tricycle-drivers-as-financial-aid |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, the Makati government converted the Makati Friendship Suites into an [[Isolation (health care)|isolation facility]] to accommodate at most 100 patients suspected of COVID-19 and is equipped with [[x-ray machine]]s, [[defibrillator]]s, and [[cardiac monitor]]s.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Layug |first1=Margaret Claire |title=Makati converts hotel into isolation facility for COVID-19 PUIs |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/731239/makati-converts-hotel-into-isolation-facility-for-covid-19-puis/story/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Malabon ====\nOn March 16, the [[Malabon]] city council approved an ordinance imposing the 8{{nbsp}}p.m. to 5{{nbsp}}a.m. curfew agreed upon by the Metro Manila Council.<ref>{{cite news |title=Malabon approves 8 pm to 5 am curfew starting March 16 |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/254723-malabon-curfew-coronavirus |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 18, Malabon Mayor [[Antolin Oreta]] ordered the city government to provide {{Philippine peso|520,000}} ($10,252.26) to each ''barangay'' for the provision of food during the Luzon-wide \"enhanced\" community quarantine. Oreta also ordered the provision of {{Philippine peso|6 million}} ($118,156.44) to the city's ''carinderia'' (food stall) owners for them to provide meals for 300 people every day for 15 days.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pedrajas |first1=Joseph Almer |title=Malabon City gov\u2019t releases food budget to barangays for needy residents |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/18/malabon-city-govt-releases-food-budget-to-barangays-for-needy-residents/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> That same day, he called on [[Maynilad Water Services]] to divert the unused [[Water supply and sanitation in the Philippines|water supply]] of closed malls and other commercial establishments to residential areas.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pedrajas |first1=Joseph Almer |title=Malabon mayor asks water concessionaires to divert mall water supply to residential areas amid COVID-19 threat |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/18/malabon-mayor-asks-water-concessionaires-to-divert-mall-water-supply-to-residential-areas-amid-covid-19-threat/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Mandaluyong ====\nOn March 16, the [[Mandaluyong]] city council passed an ordinance declaring the city under a state of calamity, after reporting three COVID-19 patients, six persons under investigation, and 125 persons under monitoring in the city.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mandaluyong declares state of calamity over spread of COVID-19 |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/16/20/mandaluyong-declares-state-of-calamity-over-spread-of-covid-19 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, Mandaluyong Mayor [[Carmelita Abalos]] ordered the release of the [[thirteenth salary]] pay to all of the city's government employees.<ref name=\"13th-month pay\">{{cite news |title=Mandaluyong, Manila gov't employees to get early 13th-month, midyear pay during community quarantine |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/17/mandaluyong-city-hall-13th-month.html |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Manila ====\n[[File:Philippine General Hospital COVID-19 ward.jpg|thumb|A ward dedicated to COVID-19 patients at the [[Philippine General Hospital]] in [[Ermita]], [[Manila]], March 28, 2020]]\n\nOn March 15, following a directive from the Metro Manila Council, [[Manila]] Mayor [[Isko Moreno]] declared a state of calamity in the city after two new cases were confirmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/254621-manila-state-calamity-new-confirmed-coronavirus-cases |title=Manila under state of calamity as city confirms 2 new coronavirus\u00a0cases |publisher=[[Rappler]] |date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, the Manila Department of Social Welfare (MDSW) began rescuing [[street people]], [[pavement dwellers]], and other homeless people, as well as people living outside the city who were unable to retreat home following the imposition of the Luzon-wide \"enhanced\" community quarantine. They took refuge at the Delpan Sports Complex in [[Tondo, Manila|Tondo]]. Mayor Isko Moreno allocated {{Philippine peso|227.5 million}} ($4.45 million) from the city's budget to assist families affected by the quarantine. MDSW Chief Re Fugoso ordered the lockdown of the Manila Boys Town Complex and the Manila Youth Reception Center in [[Ermita]] for the protection of the children and teenagers residing there amid the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tiangco |first1=Minka |title=Street dwellers given food, shelter by Manila City government |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/18/street-dwellers-given-food-shelter-by-manila-city-government/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, Mayor Isko Moreno drafted a resolution ordering the release of the mid-year bonuses of the city's government employees. He also drafted another resolution appropriating funds for the city's job order and [[Endo contractualization|contractualized workers]].<ref name=\"13th-month pay\"/>\n\nOn March 18, Mayor Isko Moreno ordered all lodging facilities in Manila to provide free accommodations for front line health professionals, such as doctors and nurses, throughout the Luzon-wide \"enhanced\" community quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Talabong |first1=Rambo |title=Isko Moreno orders Manila hotels, motels to house health workers for free |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/255062-isko-moreno-order-hotels-motels-manila-house-health-workers-for-free |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, the Manila government deployed 189 [[Electric bicycle#Tricycles|electric tricycles]] to transport front line health professionals to the city's public hospitals. In observance of the moratorium on mass public transportation, Mayor Isko Moreno clarified that the electric tricycles would operate privately to service only health workers; however, drivers of electric tricycles would receive salaries.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garcia |first1=Maria Angelica |title=Manila to deploy 189 e-trikes for COVID-19 frontliners |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/730444/manila-to-deploy-189-e-trikes-for-covid-19-frontliners/story/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Mayor Isko Moreno launched an [[Survey data collection#Online survey|online survey]] via his [[Facebook]] page inquiring Manila residents about their health status in relation to COVID-19 and their recent travel history. [[PLDT]], one of the country's major telecommunications providers, assisted the city government in providing enhanced data connectivity for the online survey service. PLDT also assisted in augmenting the hotline facility at the [[Manila City Hall]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hilario |first1=Edgard |title=Manila City Hall launches city-wide COVID-19 health survey |url=https://technology.mb.com.ph/2020/03/23/manila-city-hall-launches-city-wide-covid-19-health-survey/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn March 25, Mayor Isko Moreno called on the [[Department of Social Welfare and Development]] to assist in providing food supplies for the city's families. He stressed that the Manila government could only produce between 8,000 and 11,000 food packs, but would not suffice for the city's 350,000 families. Isko Moreno stated that the city government had already provided for about 39,000 families.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Merez |first1=Arianne |title=Isko Moreno appeals for food supplies for Manila |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/25/20/isko-moreno-appeals-for-food-supplies-for-manila |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Marikina ====\n\nOn March 16, [[Marikina]] Mayor [[Marcelino Teodoro]] announced that his government would install misting and decontamination tents across numerous public spaces in the city. Teodoro also announced that around 3,000 testing kits would be procured and that Marikina will assemble a laboratory testing center, in partnership with Manila Health Tek and the [[National Institutes of Health (Philippines)|Philippine National Institutes of Health]], to test \"[[Patient Under Investigation|patients under investigation]]\" (PUIs) for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casinas |first1=Jhon Aldrin |title=Marikina City to set up lab testing center for the detection of COVID-19 cases |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/14/marikina-city-to-set-up-lab-testing-center-for-the-detection-of-covid-19-cases/}}</ref> The Marikina government pledged to provide households with free disinfectant solutions.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Madarang |first1=Catalina Ricci |title=Marikina City, MMDA step up efforts vs COVID-19 with disinfection tents |url=https://www.interaksyon.com/trends-spotlights/2020/03/16/164301/marikina-mmda-covid19-disinfection-tents/ |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=InterAksyon |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 18, in light of the moratorium on mass public transportation during the Luzon-wide \"enhanced\" community quarantine, the Marikina government launched free shuttle bus services to ferry front line health professionals from across the city to its hospitals.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ornedo |first1=Julia Mari |title=Marikina adds more routes to free ride service for residents amid quarantine |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/730277/marikina-adds-more-routes-to-free-ride-service-for-residents-amid-quarantine/story/ |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, Mayor Teodoro announced that the Marikina government would provide free COVID-19 testing to health professionals and other suspected cases through the testing center the government assembled, effective March 24. He also announced that the government had procured a {{Philippine peso|2.7 million}} ($53,222.42) [[polymerase chain reaction]] machine specifically for testing, along with 3,000 test kits worth {{Philippine peso|4 million}} ($78,824.72).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Panti |first1=Llanesca |title=Marikina sets up lab, buys equipment to give free COVID-19 tests |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/730475/marikina-to-provide-free-covod-19-testing-to-health-workers-persons-at-risk/story/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>  \n\nOn March 26, Mayor Teodoro reported that the DOH rejected the usage of the city government's COVID-19 testing center because of its location, which had to be in a \"separate free-standing building\", but was located inside the Marikina City Health Office. Teodoro claimed that their testing center had met all the other criteria for a testing center and he even offered to cede its full operation to the DOH.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ornedo |first1=Julia Mari |title=DOH rejected COVID-19 testing center, Marikina mayor says |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/731398/doh-rejected-covid-19-testing-center-marikina-mayor-says/story/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> However, the DOH refuted the mayor's claims that they had rejected the usage of the testing center.<ref>{{cite news |title=Health dept denies rejecting Marikina's COVID-19 test lab |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/26/20/health-dept-denies-rejecting-marikinas-covid-19-test-lab |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> Nevertheless, Teodoro said that his government would relocate its testing center.<ref name=\"Marikina\">{{cite news |last1=Ayalin |first1=Adrian |title=Marikina to transfer COVID-19 testing center to separate building to comply with DOH requirements |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/27/20/marikina-to-transfer-covid-19-testing-center-to-separate-building-to-comply-with-doh-requirements |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn March 27, the Marikina government designated the defunct Marikina Hotel to serve as an isolation facility for \"patients under monitoring\" (PUMs) with suspected diagnosis of the virus.<ref name=\"Marikina\"/>\n\n==== Muntinlupa ====\n\nOn March 10, [[Muntinlupa]] Mayor [[Jaime Fresnedi]] organized a COVID-19 task force. He ordered schools and government facilities in the city to be disinfected.<ref name=\"Muntinlupa\">{{cite news |author1=[[Ignacio Bunye|Bunye, Ignacio]] |title=Muntinlupa City\u2019s response to coronavirus \u2013 a timeline |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/23/muntinlupa-citys-response-to-coronavirus-a-timeline/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, Mayor Fresnedi ordered Muntinlupa ''barangay'' officials to identify residents with recent travel history for monitoring. He also ordered officials to install isolation facilities to accommodate suspected cases of COVID-19; the city government assembled a [[field hospital]] outside the Ospital ng Muntinlupa, which became fully operational on March 18. Police officials were deployed to prevent students from entering malls, following the suspension of classes in Metro Manila.<ref name=\"Muntinlupa\"/>\n\nOn March 16, Mayor Fresnedi placed the city under a state of calamity, after confirming its first COVID-19 case.<ref>{{cite web |title=Muntinlupa City Declares State Of Calamity Due To COVID-19 Emergency |url=https://www.muntinlupacity.gov.ph/?p=18062 |publisher=City Government of Muntinlupa |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> The Muntinlupa city council approved four ordinances in relation to addressing the pandemic: the first is to prevent the hoarding and panic buying of essential goods; the second is to prohibit the sale, distribution, and consumption of alcoholic beverages during the duration of the Luzon-wide \"enhanced\" community quarantine; the third is to order the closure of all private establishments in the city, except for those providing essential goods such as supermarkets, pharmacies, and banks; and the fourth is to restrict the operation of restaurants, ''carinderias'', and other eateries to [[take-out]] only.<ref name=\"Muntinlupa anti-hoarding\"/> \n\nOn March 17, the Muntinlupa government launched free shuttle services for front line workers based in the city, deploying [[Jeepney#E-jeepneys|electric jeepneys]].<ref name=\"Muntinlupa\"/> \n\nOn March 19, Mayor Fresnedi met with the city's [[Barangay Captain]]s, instructing them to strictly implement and enforce the 8{{nbsp}}p.m. to 5{{nbsp}}a.m. curfew and social distancing measures in accordance with the national government's guidelines. A Barangay Captain also ordered the lockdown of an undisclosed subdivision in [[Alabang]] following confirmation from the DOH that two confirmed COVID-19 cases in the city are residents of that subdivision.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hicap |first1=Jonathan |title=Muntinlupa City gov\u2019t to intensify community quarantine measures |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/19/muntinlupa-city-govt-to-intensify-community-quarantine-measures/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, Mayor Fresnedi led the distribution of 1,500 food packages in [[Poblacion, Muntinlupa|Poblacion]]. Fresnedi assured the city's residents that the city government will provide food assistance to the city's \"vulnerable households\" that would last for up to three to four months. He also ordered the advanced release of the thirteenth salary pay of the city hall's employees.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hicap |first1=Jonathan |title=Muntinlupa ready to provide food assistance up to 4 months |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/20/muntinlupa-ready-to-provide-food-assistance-up-to-4-months/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, Mayor Fresnedi signed into effect an ordinance passed by the city council to impose a 24-hour city-wide curfew, superseding the 8{{nbsp}}p.m. to 5{{nbsp}}a.m. curfew.<ref>{{cite news |title=Muntinlupa placed under 24-hour curfew |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/21/muntinlupa-under-24-hour-curfew.html |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, the Muntinlupa city council passed an ordinance to convert the Ospital ng Muntinlupa into a COVID-19 testing facility. The government would procure polymerase chain reaction machines and testing kits. The city already houses the [[Research Institute for Tropical Medicine]] in Alabang, one of five medical facilities accredited by the DOH to perform COVID-19 testing in the Philippines.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hicap |first1=Jonathan |title=Muntinlupa wants to establish own COVID-19 testing center |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/24/muntinlupa-wants-to-establish-own-covid-19-testing-center/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Navotas ====\n\nPrior to President Duterte's declaration of a partial lockdown on Metro Manila, [[Navotas]] Mayor [[Toby Tiangco]] had already suspended classes at all levels in the city for March 9 as a preventive measure against the spread of COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mendoza |first1=Red |title=Navotas suspends classes due to Covid-19 outbreak |url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/03/07/news/latest-stories/navotas-suspends-classes-due-to-covid-19-outbreak/700948/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=The Manila Times |date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> Tiangco also appealed to the [[Department of Education (Philippines)|Department of Education]] to pass all students in the city for the school year.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casilao |first1=Joahna Lei |title=Navotas mayor asks DepEd to pass all students; Duque says class suspension not a good idea now |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/728716/navotas-mayor-asks-deped-to-pass-all-students-duque-says-class-suspension-not-a-good-idea-now/story/?just_in |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, the Navotas government issued an ordinance limiting the amount of work required for its government officials to work 10 hours per day for four days, effective March 16, in observance of social distancing guidelines.<ref>{{cite news |title=Navotas to implement 4-day work week for some LGU offices, employees |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/13/20/navotes-4-day-work-week-due-to-covid-19-coronavirus |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, the Navotas city council passed an ordinance imposing an 8 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew from March 16 to April 14, as agreed upon by the Metro Manila Council. It also required commercial establishments, except for those providing essential goods, to close before the start of the curfew.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gavilan |first1=Jodesz |title=Navotas City approves curfew from 8 pm to 5 am |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/254632-navotas-city-passes-curfew-ordinance-novel-coronavirus |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, the Navotas government began distributing around 18,000 food packs to the city's [[Slums in Metro Manila|informal settlers]] living in \"danger zones\" and families listed under the city's housing projects.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Paunan |first1=Jerome Carlo |title=Navotas uses 'katok' system for family food pack delivery amid quarantine |url=https://pia.gov.ph/news/articles/1036876 |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |agency=Philippine Information Agency |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn March 23, Mayor Tiangco announced that the city's government employees would receive {{Philippine peso|6,000}} ($117.41) each as compensation, totaling {{Philippine peso|6.4 million}} ($125,233.22). Tiangco also announced that their quarterly bonus payment would be released in advance.<ref>{{cite news |title=Navotas releases P6.4 million for cash aid to employees amid lockdown |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/255698-navotas-city-releases-budget-fund-incentives-employees-coronavirus |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Para\u00f1aque ====\nOn March 16, [[Para\u00f1aque]] Mayor Edwin Olivarez declared the city under a state of calamity due to the rise of COVID-19 cases in nearby areas.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Esguerra |first1=Darryl John |title=COVID-19: Para\u00f1aque City placed under state of calamity |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1243108/covid-19-paranaque-city-placed-under-state-of-calamity |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, Mayor Olivarez declared a \"total lockdown\" on the city, prohibiting visitors \"without official business\" from entering the city's premises during the Luzon-wide \"enhanced\" community quarantine. The \"total lockdown\" permits only front line offices and basic services providers to operate throughout its duration. Olivarez also requested city hall employees to go on leave.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fernando |first1=Jean |title=Para\u00f1aque City implements \u2018total lockdown\u2019 |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/17/paranaque-city-implements-total-lockdown/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, Mayor Olivarez announced that the city's front line workers, which he identified specifically as medical personnel, drug store personnel, health workers, supermarket employees, bank personnel, [[business process outsourcing]] personnel, restaurant personnel, and city government employees, would be provided with free transportation to their different workplaces.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fernando |first1=Jean |title=Para\u00f1aque City provides free transportation for city\u2019s frontliners, essential workers |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/19/paranaque-city-provides-free-transportation-for-citys-frontliners-essential-workers/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> That same day, Mayor Olivarez announced that both regular and contractualized employees in Para\u00f1aque would receive their full mid-year bonuses, in addition to a {{Philippine peso|6,000}} ($117) clothing allowance until March 23.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Abad |first1=Roderick |title=Para\u00f1aque City Hall workers get midyear bonus amid lockdown |url=https://businessmirror.com.ph/2020/03/19/paranaque-city-hall-workers-get-midyear-bonus-amid-lockdown/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=BusinessMirror |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, the Para\u00f1aque government distributed around 100,000 relief goods to 14,000 \"vulnerable households\" across the city.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fernando |first1=Jean |title=Para\u00f1aque City gov\u2019t to distribute relief goods house-to-house to vulnerable sectors |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/20/paranaque-city-govt-to-distribute-relief-goods-house-to-house-to-vulnerable-sectors/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Mayor Olivarez announced that the Para\u00f1aque government had begun imposing a 24-hour curfew to its residents.<ref>{{cite news |title=Para\u00f1aque imposes 24-hour curfew |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/23/20/paraaque-imposes-24-hour-curfew |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> The following day, a photo published by the [[San Isidro, Para\u00f1aque|San Isidro]] government circulated on social media showing alleged curfew violators in the ''barangay'' being forced to sit under the sun as penalty. Netizens have criticized the action for physical torture.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Talabong |first1=Rambo |title=LOOK: In Para\u00f1aque, curfew violators sit under the sun as punishment |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/255645-barangay-san-isidro-paranaque-curfew-violators-punished-sit-under-sun-curfew |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Pasay ====\nOn March 16, [[Pasay]] Mayor Emi Calixto-Rubiano declared the city under a state of calamity due to \"the extremely high incidence of COVID-19 cases in the city.\" The Pasay government also issued an ordinance imposing the 8 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew agreed upon by the Metro Manila Council.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nazario |first1=Dhel |title=Pasay City placed under a state of calamity |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/16/pasay-city-placed-under-a-state-of-calamity/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 18, Mayor Calixto-Rubiano ordered the advanced release of the thirteenth salary pay of city hall employees, in accordance with President Duterte's call for local government units to do so.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nazario |first1=Dhel |title=Pasay City mayor orders early release of 13th month pay, salaries of city hall employees |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/18/pasay-city-mayor-orders-early-release-of-13th-month-pay-salaries-of-city-hall-employees/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, the Pasay government announced that it collaborated with the [[Department of Trade and Industry (Philippines)|Department of Trade and Industry]] to deploy [[food cart]]s to roam around the city's 201 ''barangays'' and sell essential goods such as food and medicines, in order to limit the movement of its residents during the Luzon-wide \"enhanced\" community quarantine. The Pasay government also announced that it collaborated with the [[Philippine Army]] to provide free transportation for Pasay-based health professionals and other service front liners who work outside the city, as well as persons with disabilities and senior citizens, amid the moratorium on public transportation; the government procured 100 electric tricycles and 20 [[Mitsubishi Delica|Mitsubishi L300]] vans.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gonzales |first1=Cathrine |title=DTI to launch \u2018rolling stores\u2019 in Pasay amid quarantine |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1245125/pasay-rolling-stores-during-quarantine |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, the Pasay government ordered the installation of modular tents at the Pasay City Sports Complex and the Padre Burgos Elementary School to serve as [[Isolation (health care)|isolation units]] for COVID-19 PUIs in the city.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marquez |first1=Consuelo |title=Pasay sports complex, school transformed into isolation rooms for PUIs |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1247741/pasay-govt-on-isolation-units-for-puis |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Pasig ====\n\nOn March 9, following the confirmation of COVID-19 patient at [[The Medical City]] in the city's district of [[Ortigas Center|Ortigas]], [[Pasig]] Mayor [[Vico Sotto]] ordered city officials to implement the guidelines of the DOH and the [[World Health Organization]] in preventing the spread of the virus, including contact tracing, organizing response teams, disinfecting public spaces, and the cancellation of all public events and gatherings.<ref name=\"Sotto\">{{cite news |last1=Abellon |first1=Bam |title=Here\u2019s everything that Mayor Vico Sotto has done so far in response to COVID-19 |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/ancx/culture/spotlight/03/20/20/heres-everything-that-mayor-vico-sotto-has-done-so-far-in-response-to-covid-19 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 14, the Pasig government distributed over 500 sets of [[personal protective equipment]] to its 30 ''barangays''. The city council also approved an ordinance imposing the 8 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew agreed upon by the Metro Manila Council.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Guzman |first1=Jimmyley |title=Sprayers, protective equipment distributed to Pasig barangays |url=https://pia.gov.ph/news/articles/1036318 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |publisher=Philippine Information Agency |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, Mayor Sotto approved the calamity measure after six confirmed cases and one fatality were recorded in the city. The mayor also announced that they have ordered a mandatory isolation for the health workers of Rizal Medical Center after they were exposed to a confirmed coronavirus patient.<ref name=\"state of calamity\">{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/nation/2020/03/16/2001178/more-cities-metro-manila-under-state-calamity |title=More cities in Metro Manila under state of calamity |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=Servallos, N.J. |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, the Pasig city council approved an anti-panic buying and hoarding of essential goods ordinance.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bigtas |first1=Jannielyn Ann |title=Pasig City to implement anti-panic buying, hoarding ordinance |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/729913/pasig-city-to-implement-anti-panic-buying-hoarding-ordinance/story/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, Mayor Sotto appealed to the [[Department of Interior and Local Government]] (DILG) to allow the operation of [[Motorized tricycle (Philippines)|tricycles]] and the city's bus service to specifically transport front line health professionals and other essential service providers to the city's hospitals during the quarantine period, following the moratorium on mass public transportation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Vico Sotto rejects ban on tricycles in Pasig City amid Luzon lockdown |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/17/20/vico-sotto-rejects-ban-on-tricycles-in-pasig-city-amid-luzon-lockdown |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Pasig City sets up sanitation tents outside hospitals, provides bus service for healthcare workers |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/lifestyle/healthandwellness/730259/pasig-city-sets-up-sanitation-tents-outside-city-hall-pcgh-children-s-hospital/story/ |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> Sotto had earlier raised tricycles fares by 50 percent following the decline in residents leaving their homes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Malasig |first1=Jeline |title=Vico Sotto temporarily allows tricycles in Pasig for people reporting to work amid quarantine |url=https://www.interaksyon.com/politics-issues/2020/03/17/164402/vico-sotto-temporarily-allows-tricycles-in-pasig-for-people-reporting-to-work-amid-quarantine/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=InterAksyon |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> Tricycle drivers were mandated by the city government to transport a maximum of three passengers per ride in observance of the national government's social distancing guidelines.<ref name=\"Sotto\"/>\n\nOn March 18, Mayor Sotto pledged to give both [[Endo contractualization#Regular employment|regular]] and contractualized government employees their full salaries during the duration of the \"enhanced\" community quarantine in Luzon, while emergency front line workers would receive hazard and overtime pays.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casilao |first1=Joahna Lei |title=Pasig City Hall employees, from regular to contractual ones, to get full salaries amid enhanced quarantine |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/730108/pasig-employees-to-get-full-salaries-hazard-pay-amid-enhanced-quarantine/story/ |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> The Pasig government also assembled sanitation tents at the entrances of the city hall and two hospitals, prepared food packages containing vitamins to be distributed to the city's \"vulnerable households\",<ref name=\"Sotto\"/> and purchased three [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|octocopter drones]] to be utilized for disinfecting public spaces.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Malasig |first1=Jeline |title=Vico Sotto has been stellar with his proactive COVID-19 initiatives, and Filipinos want him to lead the whole country |url=https://www.interaksyon.com/politics-issues/2020/03/18/164558/vico-sotto-has-been-stellar-with-his-proactive-covid-19-initiatives-and-filipinos-want-him-to-lead-the-whole-country/ |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=InterAksyon |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, Mayor Sotto ordered the Dahlia Hotel in the city to be converted into a quarantine facility able to accommodate at least 300 PUMs and PUIs with mild to moderate symptoms of COVID-19.<ref name=\"Sotto\"/> That same day, the DILG rejected Mayor Sotto's appeal on operating tricycles in Pasig claiming it violates the national government's directives to observe social distancing measures.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Reysio-Cruz |first1=Matthew |title=Vico Sotto defends tricycle proposal amid DILG objection |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1245279/sotto-defends-tricycle-proposal-amid-dilg-objection |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> The Pasig government responded by commissioning two electric-powered City Optimized Managed Electric Transport jeeps to transport the city's front line workers across Pasig to its hospitals.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Reyes |first1=Kate |title=Check out Pasig's earth-friendly rides for hospital frontliners |url=https://www.spin.ph/life/cars-and-tech/pasig-city-to-provide-earth-friendly-rides-to-hospital-frontliners-a2442-20200319 |website=Spin.ph |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, Mayor Sotto announced that the Pasig government would extend the deadlines of all tax payments, rent, permits, and other obligatory submissions for two months.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kabagani |first1=Lade Jean |title=Deadline of tax payments, other gov\u2019t fees extended in Pasig City |url=http://www.canadianinquirer.net/2020/03/25/deadline-of-tax-payments-other-govt-fees-extended-in-pasig-city/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |agency=Philippine News Agency |via=''Philippine Canadian Inquirer'' |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn March 25, the Pasig government deployed five trucks transporting loads of essential goods, such as food, to different ''barangays'' in the city, where they are sold to residents. The government labeled these trucks as \"mobile ''[[palengke]]s''\", aimed at preventing the movement of people during the community quarantine. Mayor Sotto said that the essential goods sold to residents through the trucks are sourced from the vendors of the city's public markets \"to assist them generate income.\" The Pasig government also distributed about 400,000 food packs to its residents.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kabagani |first1=Lade Jean |title=Pasig City's 'mobile palengke' boosts social distancing |url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1097797 |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |agency=Philippine News Agency |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn March 26, the Pasig government announced that the city's jeepney, tricycle, and [[UV Express]] drivers would receive financial assistance of {{Philippine peso|3,000}} ($59) each for a total of {{Philippine peso|55.5 million}} ($1,092,803.32), effective March 30.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Laurel |first1=Drei |title=Thousands of Pasig City PUV drivers to get P3,000 financial aid starting next week |url=https://www.topgear.com.ph/news/motoring-news/pasig-city-puv-financial-assistance-a962-20200326 |website=Top Gear Philippines |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Quezon City ====\n\nOn March 13, [[Quezon City]] Mayor [[Joy Belmonte]] announced a state of calamity for the city following six confirmed cases of local COVID-19 transmissions.<ref>{{cite news |title=Quezon City declares state of calamity amid COVID-19 threat |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/13/qc-state-of-calamity.html |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Mayor Belmonte issued an executive order on March 15 imposing the 8 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew agreed upon by the Metro Manila Council.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tuquero |first1=Loreben |title=Belmonte imposes 8 pm to 5 am curfew in Quezon City |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/254626-joy-belmonte-imposes-curfew-quezon-city |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> The [[Quezon City University]] has been used as a quarantine site for PUIs in the city. As of March 24 at least 379,000 food packs has been distributed to residents by the Quezon City government.<ref name=\"covidqcnow72\">{{cite news |title=COVID-19 cases in QC now at 72; four die, one recovers |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/731197/covid-19-cases-in-qc-now-at-72-four-die-one-recovers/story/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=GMA News |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, the Quezon City government partnered with [[Hotel Sogo]] and the Rainbow Place Dormitory in [[Quezon City#Tandang Sora|Tandang Sora]] to provide free accommodations for service front liners, especially health professionals.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tuquero |first1=Loreben |title=Quezon City provides free lodging for health workers |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/255986-quezon-city-free-lodging-health-workers-coronavirus |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, the Quezon City government imposed an executive order prohibiting the sale, purchase, and consumption of alcoholic beverages in public places during the \"enhanced\" community quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ramos |first1=Christia Marie |title=QC imposes liquor ban until end of Luzon-wide quarantine |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1249257/qc-imposes-liquor-ban-until-end-of-luzon-wide-quarantine |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== San Juan ====\nOn March 6, the [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan]] government ordered the temporary closure of a Muslim prayer hall at the [[Greenhills Shopping Center]] after a frequent visitor of the pay hall was reported as the country's fifth case of confirmed COVID-19 diagnosis. San Juan Mayor [[Francis Zamora]] also ordered the postponement of all scheduled public events in the city.<ref>{{cite news |title=San Juan prayer hall frequented by coronavirus patient temporarily closed |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/6/san-juan-muslim-prayer-hall-coronavirus.html |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, Mayor Zamora announced that the villages of Greenhills and West Crame were identified as coronavirus hotspots after four salon workers in Greenhills tested positive for the virus. Zamora thus declared a state of calamity in the city and ordered the temporary closure of all malls in the city, as well as all churches.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casinas |first1=Jhon Aldrin |title=Zamora: Malls in San Juan City temporarily closed starting March 15; curfew ordinance to follow |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/14/zamora-malls-in-san-juan-city-temporarily-closed-starting-march-15-curfew-ordinance-to-follow/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> The city council had also passed an ordinance imposing the 8 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew agreed upon by the Metro Manila Council.<ref name=\"state of calamity\"/>\n\nOn March 26, Mayor Zamora announced that the San Juan government had reached an agreement with [[Xavier School]] to convert the San Juan City Science High School into a 100-bed isolation facility for COVID-19 PUIs in the city. Xavier School would assist the government in providing necessary medical equipment, medicines, and front line personnel.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marquez |first1=Consuelo |title=San Juan City to use public high school building as quarantine facility |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1248832/san-juan-city-to-use-high-school-building-as-quarantine-facility |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Taguig ====\nOn March 17, [[Taguig]] Mayor [[Lino Cayetano]] ordered a lockdown on the city after four of its residents tested positive for COVID-19; the lockdown only permits delivery vehicles of basic goods and supplies to enter and exit Taguig.<ref>{{cite news |title=Taguig placed on lockdown to prevent coronavirus spread |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/17/20/lockdown-taguig-coronavirus-cvoid-19-community-quarantine |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> Cayetano also said that the city government collaborated with transportation groups and ''barangays'' to organize [[Premium Point-to-Point Bus Service|point-to-point transportation services]] for its residents to access basic supplies amid the moratorium on mass public transportation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Taguig City on lockdown starting Wednesday amid COVID-19 threat |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/17/Taguig-City-lockdown-Wednesday-COVID-19.html |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, Mayor Cayetano warned the ''barangay'' officials of Taguig against collecting payment fees while issuing the city's health professionals and other essential workers special permits to freely roam around the city at any time during the Luzon-wide \"enhanced\" community quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Santos |first1=Jel |title=Mayor Cayetano stops money collection of barangays for travel permit |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/21/mayor-cayetano-stops-money-collection-of-barangays-for-travel-permit/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring the \"enhanced\" community quarantine, health workers from the Taguig health office had been distributing [[condom]]s, [[birth control pill]]s, [[Tuberculosis management|medication for tuberculosis]] and [[HIV medication|HIV]], and vitamins for [[hypertension]] and [[diabetes]] to residents for free.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marquez |first1=Consuelo |title=Sex in the time of COVID-19: Taguig City gives pills, condoms to residents |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1248796/sex-in-the-time-of-covid-19-taguig-city-gives-pills-condoms-to-residents |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Valenzuela ====\n\nOn March 13, the [[Valenzuela, Metro Manila|Valenzuela]] city council approved an ordinance prohibiting the hoarding and panic buying of essential goods.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casilao |first1=Joahna Lei |title=Anti-hoarding, anti-panic buying ordinance to be implemented in Valenzuela |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/729483/anti-hoarding-anti-panic-buying-ordinance-to-be-implemented-in-valenzuela/story/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, Valenzuela Mayor [[Rex Gatchalian]] announced the cancellation of several scheduled events, namely the Top Taxpayers and Top Job Providers\u2019 Night and Concert, Mega Job Fair, and the weekend Family Day activities in public schools, to prevent the spread of the virus amongst large crowds.<ref name=\"Caloocan, Valenzuela\"/>\n\nOn March 16, Mayor Gatchalian placed Valenzuela under a state of calamity.<ref>{{cite news |title=Valenzuela City placed under state of calamity amid COVID-19 threat |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/16/20/valenzuela-city-placed-under-state-of-calamity-amid-covid-19-threat |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, Mayor Gatchalian announced that {{Philippine peso|500\u2212700|link=yes}}-worth of vouchers would be issued to some 75,000 Valenzuela\u00f1o families for which they could use to claim essential goods at groceries.<ref>{{cite news |title=Valenzuela City to issue food vouchers during Luzon lockdown |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/video/news/03/19/20/valenzuela-city-to-issue-food-vouchers-during-luzon-lockdown |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> The city's government would also distribute food packages to families registered under the [[conditional cash transfer]] program.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Baron |first1=Gabriela |title=Valenzuela to distribute food packs to citizens at risk of poverty |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/17/valenzuela-to-distribute-food-packs-to-citizens-at-risk-of-poverty/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> Gatchalian assured the city's health professionals that they would be issued special permits for easier entry into the city borders, amid the establishment of checkpoints in accordance with the national government's directives regarding the partial lockdown.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pedrajas |first1=Joseph Almer |title=Mayor Gatchalian assures health workers of easy entry into Valenzuela despite Luzon quarantine |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/17/mayor-gatchalian-assures-health-workers-of-easy-entry-into-valenzuela-despite-luzon-quarantine/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, the Valenzuela government established two centralized isolation centers to accommodate suspected cases of COVID-19 and confirmed patients.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casilao |first1=Joahna Lei |title=Valenzuela sets up isolation centers vs. COVID-19 |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/730438/valenzuela-sets-up-isolation-centers-vs-covid-19/story/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, the Valenzuela city council passed an ordinance prohibiting the sale, distribution, and consumption of alcoholic beverages during the \"enhanced\" community quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hallare |first1=Katrina |title=Valenzuela imposes liquor ban during enhanced community quarantine period |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1248511/valenzuela-imposes-liquor-ban-during-enhanced-community-quarantine-period |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Impact ==\n[[File:Podium Mall coronavirus sign warning.jpg|thumb|A coronavirus warning sign at the entrance of [[The Podium]] mall in [[Ortigas Center]], [[Mandaluyong]], February 29, 2020]]\n\nOn March 11, the [[Wack Wack Golf and Country Club]] in Mandaluyong temporarily closed after one of its guests, a Singaporean permanent resident, was confirmed to have contracted COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mandaluyong golf club shut after guest tests positive for coronavirus |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/11/coronavirus-sanitation-wack-wack-golf-club.html |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/exclusive-philippine-golf-club-on-lockdown-after-guest-from-singapore-tests-positive | title=Philippine golf club on lockdown after Singapore guest tests positive for coronavirus| date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 14, the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Manila]] and the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Cubao|Diocese of Cubao]] announced that it would suspend the celebration of [[Mass in the Catholic Church|Masses]] and other public gatherings in all its churches \"until further notice\", in an effort to curb the spread of COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |title=Catholic churches in Metro Manila suspend masses |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/13/No-masses-Manila-archdiocese-churches-COVID-19.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> \n\nFollowing the MMDA's imposition of an area-wide curfew during the Metro Manila lockdown, mall operators [[Ayala Malls]], [[SM Supermalls]], [[Robinsons Malls]], and [[Vista Malls]] initially announced that it would shorten the operating hours of its malls in Metro Manila, from 11{{nbsp}}a.m. to 7{{nbsp}}p.m., in response.<ref>{{cite news |title=Metro Manila malls to shut down early ahead of quarantine |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/03/14/20/metro-manila-quarantine-malls-to-shut-down-early-ahead-of-quarantine |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> However, Metro Manila city governments later passed ordinances mandating the temporary closure of malls with the exception of establishments providing essential goods and services (such as supermarkets, pharmacies, and banks) from March 16 \"until further notice\", in accordance with the joint resolution passed by the Metro Manila Council regarding the lockdown.<ref>{{cite web |title=UPDATED: Which NCR malls are closed and which cities have curfew? See list |url=https://www.spin.ph/life/active-lifestyle/possible-mall-closures-eyed-as-ncr-goes-into-curfew-starting-tomorrow-a1374-20200314 |website=Spin.ph |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nPresident Duterte's March 16 declaration of a month-long \"enhanced\" community quarantine on the island of Luzon, including Metro Manila, suspended the operations of all modes of [[public transportation in Metro Manila]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=San Juan |first1=Alexandria Dennise |title=Operation of all modes of public transportation in Luzon suspended \u2013 DOTr |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/17/operation-of-all-modes-of-public-transportation-in-luzon-suspended-dotr/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> The [[Metro Rail Transit Corporation]] and [[Light Rail Transit Authority]] suspended the operations of the [[Manila Metro Rail Transit System]] and the [[Manila Light Rail Transit System]], respectively, from March 17; [[Manila Light Rail Transit System Line 1|LRT Line 1]] would resume operations on April 12, while [[Manila Metro Rail Transit System Line 3|MRT Line 3]] would lift its suspension on April 13.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jazul |first1=Noreen |title=MRT, LRT announce temporary suspension of operations |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/18/mrt-lrt-announce-temporary-suspension-of-operations/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, the [[Philippine National Police]] (PNP) reported that [[Crime in the Philippines|crime rates in Metro Manila]] decreased by almost 70 percent, according to data between March 15 to 20 during the implementation of the partial Metro Manila lockdown and the Luzon-wide \"enhanced\" community quarantine. During that period, the PNP reported only seven cases of murder, ten cases of homicide, 11 cases of physical injury (compared to 41 last year), five cases of rape (compared to 23 last year), 18 cases of robbery (compared to 50 last year), and 24 cases of theft (compared to 68 last year). The PNP attributed the decline in crime rates to the implementation of strict home quarantine measures.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rucuenco |first1=Aaron |title=Crime rate down by 70% in Metro Manila, 77.3% in Central Luzon due to lockdown |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/22/crime-rate-down-by-70-in-metro-manila-77-3-in-central-luzon-due-to-lockdown/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Department of Environment and Natural Resources]] (DENR) reported that the [[air quality index]] of different cities in Metro Manila had improved, following the implementation of the \"enhanced\" community quarantine on Luzon. The cities with the lowest amounts of inhalable [[PM10|coarse particulate matter]] (PM<sub>10</sub>) were Para\u00f1aque (7), Marikina (9), San Juan (17), Malabon (22), Taguig (32), and Pasay (43), all reporting \"good\" values of air quality; meanwhile, the cities of Pasig (53), Makati (54), Las Pi\u00f1as (86), and Northern Caloocan (92) all reported \"moderate/fair\" values. The DENR collected the data after photos surfaced on social media depicting [[smog]]-free skylines of some of the aforementioned cities, which is likely a result of minimized activity due to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Laurel |first1=Drei |title=DENR data shows improved air quality in Metro Manila due to quarantine |url=https://www.topgear.com.ph/news/motoring-news/denr-air-quality-metro-manila-a962-20200325 |website=Top Gear Philippines |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Philippines}}\n*[[2020 Luzon enhanced community quarantine]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\n* [https://www.doh.gov.ph/2019-nCoV Updates on Novel Coronavirus Disease (COVID-19)] by the [[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health]], Situation tracker, updated daily.\n* [https://corona.arrangy.com Worldwide Coronavirus Map, confirmed Cases] \u2013 Map the route paths of coronavirus confirmed cases.\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{Rodrigo Duterte}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:History of Metro Manila]]\n[[Category:Health in Metro Manila]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by city|Manila]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Metro Manila}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Philippine English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Metro Manila\n| map1            = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Metro Manila.svg\n| legend1         = {{center|Map of cities with confirmed coronavirus cases by hospital of admission (as of March 12)}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Metro Manila]]\n| first_case      = [[Manila]]\n| arrival_date    = January 30, 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=30|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| recovery_cases  = 45\n| deaths          = 101\n| confirmed_cases = 670\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = https://www.doh.gov.ph/2019-nCoV\n}}\n\nThe first confirmed case of the [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in the [[Philippines]] was recorded in [[Metro Manila]] on January 30, 2020. It involved a 38-year-old Chinese woman from [[Wuhan]], the origin of the disease, who arrived in [[Manila]] after travelling to [[Cebu City]] and [[Dumaguete]] in central Philippines from [[Hong Kong]].<ref name=\"abs1\">{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/01/30/20/philippines-confirms-first-case-of-new-coronavirus |title=Philippines confirms first case of new coronavirus |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |author=Sabillo, K. |date=30 January 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref> Three days later, the [[Department of Health (Philippines)|Philippine Department of Health]] (DOH) confirmed that a second Chinese national tested positive for COVID-19, identified as the 44-year-old male companion of the first confirmed patient.<ref name=\"gma1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/724482/philippines-confirms-2nd-novel-coronavirus-case-patient-dies/story/ |title=Philippines confirms 2nd novel coronavirus case, 1st death outside China |publisher=[[GMA News]] |author=Colcol, E. |date=2 February 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\nBoth patients received treatment at Manila's [[San Lazaro Hospital, Manila|San Lazaro Hospital]] with the latter being reported to have died from the disease on February 2, becoming the first known fatality outside [[China]].<ref name=\"gma1\"/> On March 6, the DOH reported the first case of local community transmission of the deadly virus, a 62-year-old Filipino man from suburban [[Cainta]], [[Rizal]], just east of Metro Manila, with no prior travel history to affected countries.<ref name=\"cnn1\">{{cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/6/Philippines-coronavirus-local-case.html |title=Philippines records its first local case of coronavirus |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |author=Tan, L. |date=6 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref> He and his 59-year-old Filipino wife were initially admitted to the Cardinal Santos Medical Center in [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan]] where they were diagnosed with the virus before being transferred to the [[Research Institute for Tropical Medicine]] in [[Muntinlupa]] where they both died on March 11.<ref name=\"philstar2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/12/2000450/doh-first-local-transmission-wife-among-three-new-covid-19-deaths |title=First local COVID-19 transmission case, wife among 3 new deaths in Philippines |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=San Juan, R. |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, 2020, following the declaration of a public health emergency, Philippine President [[Rodrigo Duterte]] placed the entire capital region under community [[quarantine]] for 30 days starting March 15, 2020.<ref name=\"philstar1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/12/2000209/travel-and-manila-suspended-march-15-code-red-sublevel-2-raised-over-covid-19 |title=Travel to and from Manila suspended from March 15 as Code Red Sublevel 2 raised over COVID-19 |last=Luna |first=Franco |website=philstar.com |access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Most areas in Metro Manila have also issued curfews to help limit the spread of the virus.<ref name=\"gma2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/729731/manila-to-have-curfew-from-8-p-m-5-a-m-amid-covid-19-threat-says-mayor-isko/story/ |title=Several Metro Manila LGUs impose 8 p.m.-5 a.m. COVID-19 curfew |publisher=[[GMA News]] |author=Rita, J. |date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 29, 2020, there have been 1,546 confirmed cases of COVID-19 in the Philippines, 670 of which are residents of Metro Manila. There have been 101 reported deaths, with [[Quezon City]] and San Juan reporting the most fatalities. 45 people have recovered.<ref name=\"COVID-19 tracker\">{{cite web |title=COVID-19 Case Tracker |url=https://ncovtracker.doh.gov.ph/ |website=doh.gov.ph |publisher=[[Department of Health (Philippines)]] |accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Timeline ==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable floatright <!---mw-collapsible--->\" style=\"text-align:left; font-size:90%; width:auto; clear:right; margin:0 0 0.5em 1em;\"\n|+COVID-19 cases in NCR, Philippines<ref name=\"COVID-19 tracker\"/><br/><small>by city/municipality of residence<br/>Updated March 31, 2020 11:00 pm UTC+8</small>\n! {{abbr|LGU|Local government unit}}\n! {{Hover title|Confirmed cases|Cases}}\n! Deaths\n! {{abbr|Recov.|Recoveries}}\n|-\n| [[Caloocan]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 28\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 8\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 4\n|-\n| [[Las Pi\u00f1as]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 27\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 2\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 3\n|-\n| [[Makati]]\n| style=\"text