{"title_page": "Leptaena", "text_new": "{{Automatic taxobox\n| fossil_range = {{fossil range|Darriwilian|Emsian|latest=Tournaisian}}\n| image = Leptaena romboidalis 4.jpg\n| image_caption = ''Leptaena rhomboidalis''\n| taxon = Leptaena\n| authority = Dalman, 1828\n| subdivision_ranks = Species\n| subdivision = \n<center>See [[#Species|Species]]</center>\n}}\n\n'''''Leptaena''''' is an [[extinct]] [[genus]] of mid-sized [[brachiopod]] that existed from the [[Darriwilian|Dariwilian epoch]] to the [[Emsian|Emsian epoch]]<ref name='Smithsonian'>{{cite web |last1=Plaza-Torres |first1=Stephanie |last2=Darroch |first2=Simon |last3=Wagner |first3=Peter |title=Family tree of a mass extinction survivor: Phylogenetic analysis of the brachiopod genus Leptaena |url=https://naturalhistory.si.edu/sites/default/files/media/file/2015-plaza-torres-poster.pdf |publisher=Smithsonian |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hoel |first1=Ole |title=Palaeobiology of Silurian Leptaeninae (Brachiopoda) from Gotland, Sweden |journal=Hindawi Paleontology Journal |date=21 January 2014 |volume=Volume 2014 |doi=10.1155/2014/716053 |url=https://www.hindawi.com/journals/paleontology/2014/716053/ |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>, though some specimens have been found in [[strata]] as late in age as the [[Tournasian|Tournasian epoch]].<ref name='Smithsonian'/><ref name='PBD'>[https://paleobiodb.org/classic/basicTaxonInfo?taxon_no=319542 Paleobiology Database]</ref> Like some [[Strophomenida|Strophomenids]], ''Lepteana's'' members were [[epifauna|epifaunal]], meaning they lived on top of the seafloor, not buried within it, and were [[suspension feeder|suspension feeders]].<ref name='Atlas'>{{cite web |last1=Stigall |first1=Alycia |title=Leptaena |url=http://www.ordovicianatlas.org/atlas/brachiopoda/strophomenata/strophomenida/rafinesquinidae/leptaena/ |website=Atlas of Ordovician Life |publisher=National Science Foundation |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> \n\n==Physical Description==\n''Leptaena'' usually have concentric wrinkling and concentric lines on the shell. ''Leptaena'' have a concavo-convex profile, and are sometimes Semiquadrate to semielliptical. The Cardinal Process is split in two and the hinge line is straight.<ref name='Atlas'/> Their width is usually greater than their length, like most [[Strophomenida|Strophomenids]]. \n\n==Distribution==\n''Leptaena'' fossils have been found on every [[continent]] except [[Antarctica]].<ref name=PBD/><ref>[https://www.gbif.org/species/8338992 Global Biodiversity Information Facility]</ref><ref name='Fossilworks'>[http://fossilworks.org/bridge.pl?a=home Fossilworks]</ref> \n\n==Species==\n''Leptaena'' was an increbibly diverse genus, with over 70 recognized species and [[subgenus|subgenera]]. Selected species in the genus ''Leptaena'' include:<ref name='PBD'/><ref name='Fossilworks'/><ref>[http://www.catalogueoflife.org/annual-checklist/2019/browse/tree/id/a46215ccac957d327beae93d4a649dea Catalog of Life]</ref>\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n<!--*'''Subgenus ''Leptaena'''''\n-->\n*''[[Leptaena acuticuspidata|L. acuticuspidata]]'' <small></small>\n*''[[Leptaena aequalis|L. aequalis]]'' <small></small>\n*''[[Leptaena alliku|L. alliku]]'' <small></small>\n*''[[Leptaena amelia|L. amelia]]'' <small></small>\n*''[[Leptaena analogaeformis|L. analogaeformis]]'' <small></small>\n*''[[Leptaena arberae|L. arberae]]'' <small></small>\n*''[[Leptaena argentina|L. argentina]]'' <small></small>\n*''[[Leptaena borghiana|L. borghiana]]'' <small></small>\n*''[[Leptaena boyaca|L. boyaca]]'' <small></small>\n*''[[Leptaena contermina|L. contermina]]'' <small></small>\n*''[[Leptaena convexa|L. convexa]]'' <small></small>\n*''[[Leptaena cooperi|L. cooperi]]'' <small></small>\n*''[[Leptaena croma|L. croma]]'' <small></small>\n*''[[Leptaena cryptoides|L. cryptoides]]'' <small></small>\n*''[[Leptaena dejecta|L. dejecta]]'' <small></small>\n*''[[Leptaena delicata|L. delicata]]'' <small></small> \n*''[[Leptaena electra|L.